        {
            "id" : "77597956",
            "text" : [ "<span class=\"smGameTextTitleSize\">Validating HYPOTHESIS 3 (8/8)</span><p class=\"smGameTextSize\">Despite working within the field of History, a human science, we have also utilized Biology, Geography, Physics, and Chemistry to validate this hypothesis. However, it was not possible to identify any texts naming the first inhabitants, as writing systems did not yet exist.</p>", "<p class=\"smGameTextSize\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection smGameTextSize\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\">?</div><div class=\"first_steps_reflection\"><b>Regarding Indigenous Peoples</b><br />Is it possible to propose that people lived in a place without any written records?</div></div></p>" ],
            "desc": [ "A person without a known name might cause discomfort, but it is impossible to disregard the evidence indicating that humans lived on the continent for millennia." ],
            "next" : "92acdf0c",
            "prev" : null,
            "jumpTo" : null,
            "answer": 1,
            "score" : 2,
            "position": "top"
        },
        {
            "id" : "92acdf0c",
            "text" : [ "<span class=\"smGameTextTitleSize\">Validating HYPOTHESIS 4 (1/3)</span><p class=\"smGameTextSize\">When Fray Bartolomé de las Casas wrote about the discovery, he claimed that God gave Columbus <i>\"the keys to open the sea and discover new lands\"</i> (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('daaaf7ba-7319-463b-a30b-55b14dbbad94'); return false;\">Casas, Bartolomé de las F, <span class=\"htdate\"></span>, pp. 471</a>)</p>", "<p class=\"smGameTextSize\">The <i>Saga of the Greenlanders</i> also mentions <i>\"Vinland\"</i> and attributes its discovery to Bjarni Herjolfsson (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('db596dfb-03b5-46c5-8cbf-446614462c91'); return false;\">Grænlendinga saga</a> ; <a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('c63c9082-4a2f-40bf-962f-6db0b8703253'); return false;\">JÓHANNESSON, J., & Oleson, T. J., <span class=\"htdate\"></span> </a>).</p>" ],
            "desc": null,
            "next" : "7e4710ea",
            "prev" : null,
            "jumpTo" : null,
            "answer": 0,
            "score" : 1,
            "position": "center"
        },
        {
            "id" : "7e4710ea",
            "text" : [ "<span class=\"smGameTextTitleSize\">Validating HYPOTHESIS 4 (2/3)</span><p class=\"smGameTextSize\">As mentioned in <b>HYPOTHESIS 3</b>, people were already present on the continent before the arrival of Europeans. In this context, it is important to define the meaning of \"discover\":</p>", "<p class=\"smGameTextSize\"><i>\"To find information, a place, or an object, especially for the first time\"</i> (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillPrimarySource('cefb324d-a55f-40c2-89be-1ba8f761af60'); return false;\">Cambridge Dictionary, \"discover, verb\", <span class=\"htdate\"></span></a>)).</p>" ],
            "desc": null,
            "next" : "2a8a549e",
            "prev" : "92acdf0c",
            "jumpTo" : null,
            "answer": 0,
            "score" : 1,
            "position": "center"
        },
        {
            "id" : "2a8a549e",
            "text" : [ "<span class=\"smGameTextTitleSize\">Validating HYPOTHESIS 4 (3/3)</span></p>", "<p><center><div class=\"first_steps_reflection_parent\"><div class=\"first_steps_reflection question_mark\"><i class=\"fa-solid fa-brain\"></i></div><b>Reflection 2: On the scope of discovery</b><br />The dictionary definition of \"discover\" is not limited to a single person, allowing different individuals to discover something at different times. In this context, why should we not consider an inclusive perspective that recognizes multiple discoveries?<br /></div></div></center></p>" ],
            "desc": null,
            "next" : "1fcc08c9",
            "prev" : "7e4710ea",
            "jumpTo" : null,
            "answer": 1,
            "score" : 1,
            "position": "center"
        },
        {
            "id" : "1fcc08c9",
            "text" : [ "<span class=\"smGameTextTitleSize\">The theory (1/2)</span><p class=\"smGameTextSize\">In this analysis, we will not use tables. Instead, we will develop the theory based on the study.</p>", "<p class=\"smGameTextSize\">To rigorously address the concept of the \"<b>first person to discover</b>\", we must recognize that both Iberians (<b>HYPOTHESIS 1</b>) and Nordics (<b>HYPOTHESIS 2</b>) arrived on the continent with other <i>Homo sapiens</i> already present (<a href=\"#\" onclick=\"htCleanSources(); htFillReferenceSource('7fb1905e-d1b0-4561-8953-266e7657f604'); return false;\">Al Jazeera, <span class=\"htdate\"></span></a>). Therefore, our theory should be grounded in <b>HYPOTHESIS 3</b>.</p>", "<p class=\"smGameTextSize\">However, given that the definition of \"discover\" is not overly restrictive, it is reasonable to accept that different individuals could have discovered the continent at different times. Thus, <b>HYPOTHESIS 4</b> is the most precise.</p>" ],
            "desc": null,
            "next" : "6bb8aabf",
            "prev" : null,
            "jumpTo" : null,
            "answer": 1,
            "score" : 1,
            "position": "top"
        },
        {
            "id" : "66ad3092",
            "text" : [ "<span class=\"smGameTextTitleSize\">The theory (2/2)</span><p class=\"smGameTextSize\"><b>THEORY</b>: Although we do not know the name of the first person to see America (<i>Abya Ayala</i>), it is clear that various people arrived on the continent without prior knowledge of it. Consequently, there were multiple discoveries.</p>", "<p class=\"smGameTextSize\"><center><i class=\"fa-solid fa-medal\" style=\"color:gold; font-size: 5vw\"></i></center></p>" ],
            "desc": null,
            "next" : null,
            "prev" : null,
